Averievite is characterized by the presence of a backbone composed of Cu$_{5}$O$_{2}$ clusters and either VO$_{4}$ or PO$_{4}$ tetrahedra. The exact structure depends on the atoms added to the backbone.  We have included several averievite structures in the Encyclopedia: \begin{itemize} \item \href{current_web_home_dir/A5B10C2_mP68_14_5e_10e_2e-001}{Stoiberite}, Cu$_{5}$(VO$_{4}$)$_{2}$, \item \href{current_web_home_dir/A18B15C10D2_hP45_164_ij_abcdei_2di_d-001}{(ClCu)$_{2}$Cu$_{5}$O$_{2}$(VO$_{4}$)$_{2}$} (this structure), \item \href{current_web_home_dir/A2B7C10D2_hP21_143_2a_2abcd_2b2c2d_bc-001}{Cu$_{5}$O$_{2}$(VO$_{4}$)$_{2}$$\cdot$CuCl$_{2}$}, \item \href{current_web_home_dir/AB3C5D10E2_hP21_164_a_bc_de_2di_d-001}{(CsCl)Cu$_{5}$O$_{2}$(PO$_{4}$)$_{2}$}, \item \href{current_web_home_dir/AB2C5D10E2_mP40_14_a_e_c2e_5e_e-001}{Monoclinic (CsCl)Cu$_{5}$O$_{2}$(VO$_{4}$)$_{2}$}, \item \href{current_web_home_dir/A2B7C10D20E4_hP86_147_ae_c2g_d3g_2d6g_dg-001}{Trigonal (CsCl)Cu$_{5}$O$_{2}$(VO$_{4}$)$_{2}$}, and \item \href{current_web_home_dir/AB5C2D10E2_mC80_15_e_e2f_f_5f_f-001}{(KBr)Cu$_{5}$O$_{2}$(VO$_{4}$)$_{2}$}. \end{itemize} ~ \vspace{-.25in} 
 See (Starov, 1997), (Botana, 2018), and (Kornyakov, 2021) for more information. 
 While all averievites have considerable disorder, (ClCu)$_{2}$Cu$_{5}$O$_{2}$(VO$_{4}$)$_{2}$ has more disorder than most: \begin{itemize} \item The Cu I (1a) site is occupied 49.3\% of the time \item The Cu II (1b) occupation is 53.6\%  \item The Cu III (2c) occupation is 35.6\% \item The Cu IV (2d) occupation is 36.0\% \item The Cl I (6i) occupation is 8.0\% \item The Cu VI (6i) occupation is 21.0\% \item The Cl II (12i) occupation is 16.4\%. \end{itemize} ~ \vspace{-.25in} 
 These occupations lead to the compound Cl$_{2.064}$Cu$_{6.721}$O$_{10}$V$_{2}$ which becomes (Cl$_{2.064}$Cu$_{1.721}$)Cu$_{5}$O$_{2}$(VO$_{4}$)$_{2}$ in standard averievite notation. 
 We have shifted the origin by 1/2 c $\hat{z}$, swaping the (1a) and (1b) sites and moving the experimental Cu (3f) site to Cu (3e).
